<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P>This is an application for judicial review, pursuant to s. 18 and 18.1 of the <EM>Federal Courts Act</EM>, in respect of a decision made by Mr. L. Beck, Team Leader at the Taxpayer Relief Centre of Expertise, Appeals Branch of the Canada Revenue Agency (the &ldquo;<BOLD>CRA</BOLD>&rdquo;), who, acting on behalf of the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Minister</BOLD>&rdquo;), on July 19, 2017, denied the Applicant's request dated May 4, 2017 for the following relief pursuant to subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (the &ldquo;<BOLD>IT</BOLD>A&rdquo;):
<P1>A. The Cancellation of interest for the 2002 taxation year from January 01, 2006 to May 1, 2008 and March 5, 2013 to October 5, 2016;</P1>
<P1>B. The Cancellation of interest for the 2003 taxation year from January 01, 2006 to May 1, 2008 and June 25, 2011 to October 5, 2016; and</P1>
<P1>C. No agreement to waive any interest that would otherwise accrue on the 2002 and 2003 tax years starting on May 25, 2016.</P1></P>
<P>The Applicant makes an application pursuant to s. 18 and 18.1 of the <EM>Federal Courts Act</EM> to seek the following orders:
<P1>A. An order referring the matter back to the Minister to redetermine CRA's decision of July 19, 2017 to not grant the requested relief on its merits and that such redetermination be carried out by a person or persons previously uninvolved with the tax affairs of the Applicant, his wife, or Thomson 28 Co. Ltd. (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Corporation</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>B. An order for the reasonable and proper costs of this Application as this Honourable Court in its discretion may award; and</P1>
<P1>C. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
<P>The grounds for the application are:
<QUOTE><BLOCK1><TI><EM>First Notice of Objection</EM></TI>
<P>1. On February 1, 2008, the Applicant was assessed by the CRA under s. 152(7) of the ITA for the 2002 and 2003 tax years.</P>
<P>2. On May 2, 2008, the Applicant's then lawyer&mdash;Mr. John David Boute&mdash;filed an Application for an Extension of Time to file a Notice of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 tax years (the &ldquo;<BOLD>First Objection</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. At the time of filing the First Objection, the Applicant requested that this matter be held in abeyance pending the resolution of his appeal in the Tax Court of Canada for the 1999 to 2001 tax years on the grounds that there were common issues in all of the years (the &ldquo;<BOLD>TCC Appeal</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. On February 18, 2009, the appeals officer assigned to the file, Ms. Alice Tao (&ldquo;<BOLD>Appeals Officer Tao</BOLD>&rdquo;), requested that the Applicant prepare and submit T1 income tax returns for the 2002 tax year for her review.</P>
<P>5. On June 25, 2009, a Notice of Confirmation was issued for the 2002 tax year (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Confirmation</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>Tax Court of Canada Decision for 1999 to 2001</EM></TI>
<P>6. On November 20, 2009, the Tax Court of Canada rendered its decision with respect to the TCC Appeal.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>Second Notice of Objection</EM></TI>
<P>7. On April 8, 2010, a Consequential Reassessment for the 2002 tax year was issued as a result of the decision in the TCC Appeal.</P>
<P>8. On June 24, 2011, the Applicant's new lawyer&mdash;Mr. Nick Ranieri&mdash;filed an Application for an Extension of Time to file a Notice of Objection for the 1999 to 2003 and 2009 tax years (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Second Objection</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>ITA s. 165(1.2) Applied to 2002 Tax Year</EM></TI>
<P><P1>9. On January 4, 2012, the CRA acknowledged receipt of the Second Objection and refused to accept the objection for the 2002 tax year citing the application of ITA s. 165(1.2).</P1>
<P1>10. On August 10, 2012, an appeals officer&mdash;Ms. Maryam Aman (&ldquo;<BOLD>Appeals Officer Aman</BOLD>&rdquo;)&mdash;requested particulars in respect of the Applicant's objection for the 2009 tax year only.</P1>
<P1>11. On December 19, 2012, a new appeals officer&mdash;Ms. Hanaa Farag (&ldquo;<BOLD>Appeals Officer Farag</BOLD>&rdquo;)&mdash;was assigned to the Second Objection.</P1>
<P1>12. On January 14, 2013, Mr. Ranieri wrote to Appeals Officer Farag stating that ITA s. 165(1.2) was inapplicable to the Applicant's 2002 tax year.</P1>
<P1>13. On January 15, 2013, Appeals Officer Farag wrote to Mr. Ranieri to request further information and explanations.</P1>
<P1>14. On February 1, 2013, Mr. Ranieri in response to Appeals Officer Farag's January 15, 2013 letter, again repeated his submission that ITA s. 165(1.2) was not applicable to the Applicant's 2002 tax year.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>ITA s. 165(1.2) Inapplicable to 2002 Tax Year</EM></TI>
<P><P1>15. On March 5, 2013, Appeals Officer Farag wrote to the Applicant and finally informed him that the CRA was now in agreement with him. They agreed that the objection for the 2002 tax year was valid as a result of a consequential reassessment stemming from the TCC Appeal.</P1>
<P1>16. On April 10, 2013, Mr. Ranieri submitted the Applicant's T1 income tax returns for the 2002 tax year to Appeals Officer Farag by fax.</P1>
<P1>17. On April 12, 2013, Appeals Officer Farag provided Mr. Ranieri with a final summary of the Notices of Objection for the 1999 through 2002 tax years.</P1>
<P1>18. On February 3, 2014, the Applicant filed a request for a reassessment pursuant to ITA s. 152(4.2) for the 2002 tax year.</P1>
<P1>19. On May 5, 2014, Appeals Officer Aman wrote to the Applicant requesting that he provide supporting documentation with respect to the 2002 tax year.</P1>
<P1>20. On June 4, 2014, Mr. Ranieri provided Appeals Officer Aman with financial statements indicating the Applicant's pay in the 2002 tax year.</P1>
<P1>21. On the same day, Mr. Ranieri wrote to Appeals Officer Aman to provide written confirmation of the Applicant's position with respect to the 2002 tax year.</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>First Taxpayer Relief Request Filed</EM></TI>
<P>22. On July 3, 2014, the Applicant filed a Request for Taxpayer Relief for the 2002 tax year on the basis that the CRA had made a delay in processing his objection and that the Applicant's then lawyer, Mr. Boute, had misinformed him about filing an appeal for the 2003 tax year (the &ldquo;<BOLD>First Relief Request</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>Second Notice of Objection Allowed in Part</EM></TI>
<P>23. On July 24, 2014, the CRA allowed the Applicant's 2002 tax year objection in part.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>Second Taxpayer Relief Request Filed</EM></TI>
<P>24. On May 7, 2015, the CRA rejected the First Relief Request for the following reasons:
<P1>a. a history of non-compliance with his tax obligations;</P1>
<P1>b. a balance had knowingly been allowed to exist on which arrears interest had accrued;</P1>
<P1>c. a reasonable amount of care had not been exercised; and</P1>
<P1>d. actions were not taken to quickly remedy any delay or omission.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>Third Taxpayer Relief Request Filed</EM></TI>
<P>25. On May 25, 2016, TaxChambers LLP filed, on behalf of the Applicant, another Taxpayer Relief Request (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Third Relief Request</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>26. The Third Relief Request asked for two types of relief:
<P1>a. the cancellation of interest that accrued from May 25, 2006 to May 25, 2016 on any balance in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years; and</P1>
<P1>b. the waiver of all future interest on any balance in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years.</P1></P>
<P>27. On December 05, 2016, the CRA responded to the Third Relief Request as follows:
<P1>a. Arrears interest for the 2002 tax year was cancelled for the period between June 24, 2011 and March 06, 2013 due to possible CRA delay (&ldquo;<BOLD>Third Request Decision</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>b. All other requested relief was denied. In particular:
<P2>i. no relief was granted for the 2002 tax year from January 01, 2006 to June 24, 2011;</P2>
<P2>ii. no relief was granted for the 2002 tax year from March 5, 2013 to October 5, 2016;</P2>
<P2>iii. no relief was granted for the 2003 tax year from January 01, 2006 to the present; and</P2>
<P2>iv. no agreement to waive any interest that would otherwise accrue on the 2002 and 2003 tax years starting on May 25, 2016.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><EM>Second Level Review of Third Relief Request</EM></TI>
<P>28. On May 4, 2017, TaxChambers LLP filed, on behalf of the Applicant, a second level review of the Third Request Decision (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Second Level Review Request</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>29. The Second Level Review Request asked for two types of relief:
<P1>a. the cancellation of interest that accrued in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years for the following periods:
<P2>i. from May 25, 2006 to June 24, 2011; and</P2>
<P2>ii. from March 6, 2013 to the present date.</P2></P1>
<P1>b. The waiver of all future interest on any balance in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years.</P1></P>
<P>30. On July 19, 2017, CRA responded to the Second Level Review request as follows:
<P1>a. Arrears interest for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years were cancelled for the period between May 2, 2008 and June 24, 2011 due to the actions of CRA (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Second Level Review Response</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>b. All other requested relief was denied. In particular:
<P2>i. no relief was granted for the 2002 tax year from January 01, 2006 to May 1, 2008;</P2>
<P2>ii. no relief was granted for the 2002 tax year from March 5, 2013 to October 5, 2016;</P2>
<P2>iii. no relief was granted for the 2003 tax year from January 01, 2006 to May 1, 2008;</P2>
<P2>iv. no relief was granted for the 2003 tax year from June 25, 2011 to October 5, 2016; and</P2>
<P2>v. no agreement to waive any interest that would otherwise accrue on the 2002 and 2003 tax years starting on May 25, 2016.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK1>
