<BLOCK0><TI>APPLICANT'S MEMORANDUM OF FACT AND LAW</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. On July 19, 2017, the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Minister</BOLD>&rdquo;) partially granted the Applicant's request to cancel interest under subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (the &ldquo;<BOLD><EM>ITA</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, RSC 1985, c 1 (5th Supp).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>2. On July 19, 2017, the Minister cancelled interest that had accrued between May 2, 2008, and June 24, 2011, for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.</P>
<P>3. The Minister had previously cancelled interest from June 24, 2011, to March 5, 2013, for the 2002 taxation year as a result of the Applicant's first Taxpayer Relief Request dated May 25, 2016.</P>
<P>4. The Applicant submits that the Minister's July 19, 2017, decision to not cancel additional interest for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years was an unreasonable exercise of the Minister's discretion.</P>
<P>5. The Applicant's request for relief was based on having experienced significant CRA delays in the processing of his T1 Income Tax Returns and Notices of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.</P>
<P>6. The Applicant submits that the Minister's delegate based her decision on a gross misapprehension of the facts as to the existence and cause of the said delays experienced by the Applicant.</P>
<P>7. Additionally, the Applicant submits that the Minister's decision was unreasonable upon a fair understanding of the events that transpired in the processing of his T1 Income Tax Returns and Notices of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART I: STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. Mr. Robert Jewett (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Applicant</BOLD>&rdquo;) was at all material times a resident of Canada for tax purposes.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>First Notice of Objection</TI>
<P>9. On February 1, 2008, the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Minister</BOLD>&rdquo;) issued Notices of Assessment to the Applicant for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years under subsection 152(7) of the <EM>ITA</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 2 and Exhibit A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. On May 2, 2008, the Applicant's then lawyer, Mr. John David Boute, filed an Application for an Extension of Time to file a Notice of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years (the &ldquo;<BOLD>First Objection</BOLD>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 3 and Exhibit B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. At the time of filing the First Objection, Mr. Boute requested that the First Objection be held in abeyance pending the resolution of the Appeal in the Tax Court of Canada for the 1999 to 2001 taxation years (the &ldquo;<BOLD>TCC Appeal</BOLD>&rdquo;) because there were common issues in all of the years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 4 and Exhibit B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. On February 18, 2009, a Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;<BOLD>CRA</BOLD>&rdquo;) Appeals Officer, Ms. Alice Tao, was assigned to the First Objection. Ms. Tao requested that the Applicant prepare and submit T1 income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years for her review.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 5 and Exhibit C.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. On June 25, 2009, the Minister issued a Notice of Confirmation for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years, thereby closing the First Objection file with CRA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 6 and Exhibit D.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Tax Court of Canada Decision for 1999 to 2001</TI>
<P>14. On November 20, 2009, the Tax Court of Canada rendered its decision with respect to the TCC Appeal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 7 and Exhibit E.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Second Notice of Objection</TI>
<P>15. On April 8, 2010, a consequential Notice of Reassessment for the 2002 taxation year was issued as a result of the decision in the TCC Appeal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 8 and Exhibit F.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. On June 24, 2011, the Applicant's new lawyer, Mr. Nick Ranieri, filed an Application for an Extension of Time to file a Notice of Objection for the 1999 to 2003 and 2009 taxation years (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Second Objection</BOLD>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 9 and Exhibit G.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. On January 4, 2012, the CRA acknowledged receipt of the Second Objection and refused to accept the Second Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years under subsection 165(1.2) of the <EM>ITA</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 10 and Exhibit H.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. On August 10, 2012, a CRA Appeals Officer, Ms. Maryam Aman, was assigned to the Second Objection. Ms. Aman requested particulars in respect of 2009 taxation year only.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 11 and Exhibit I.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. On December 19, 2012, another CRA Appeals Officer, Mr. Hanaa Farag, was assigned to the Second Objection.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para 12 and Exhibit J.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. Between December 19, 2012, and March 5, 2013, Ms. Farag and Mr. Ranieri exchanged letters related to the validity of the Second Objection concerning the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at Exhibits J, K, L, M, and N</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. On March 5, 2013, Ms. Farag confirmed that the Second Objection was valid concerning the 2001 taxation year, but was invalid concerning the 2003 taxation year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, at para. 16 and Exhibit N.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. On April 10, 2013, Mr. Ranieri faxed the Applicant's T1 income tax returns for the 2002 and 2002 taxation years to Ms. Farag.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit O.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. On April 12, 2013, Ms. Farag wrote to Mr. Ranieri and provided a summary concerning the Applicant's Notices of Objection for the 1999 through 2001 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit Q.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. On May 5, 2014, Ms. Aman wrote to the Applicant requesting schedules and supporting documentation related to the T1 income tax return provided by the Applicant and Mr. Ranieri.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit S.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. On June 4, 2014, Mr. Ranieri faxed supporting documentation to Ms. Aman concerning the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2002 taxation year, along with submissions in support of the 2002 Notice of Objection.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit T &amp; U.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. On July 24, 2014, Ms. Aman wrote to the Applicant informing him that his Notice of Objection for the 2002 taxation year was allowed in part.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit W.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Request for Reassessment</TI>
<P>27. On March 16, 2012, the Applicant filed T1 income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, tab I, page 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. On September 27, 2013, Mr. Ranieri was contacted by Mr. Pagonis, who was assigned by CRA to review the Applicant's T1 income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit R.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. On December 6, 2013, the Applicant was informed by Mr. Pagonis that his request for a reassessment of the 2002 and 2003 taxation years were denied.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit R.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Taxpayer Relief Requests</TI>
<P>30. On July 3, 2014, the Applicant filed a Taxpayer Relief Request for the 2003 taxation year on the basis of CRA delay and due to the actions of Mr. Boute.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit V.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>31. On May 7, 2015, the CRA rejected the Applicant's July 3, 2014, Taxpayer Relief Request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit X.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. On May 25, 2016, TaxChambers LLP filed, on behalf of the Applicant, a Taxpayer Relief Request for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit Y.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>33. On December 5, 2016, the CRA partially allowed the Applicant's May 25, 2016, Taxpayer Relief Request by cancelling interest that accrued between June 24, 2011, and March 6, 2013, but only for the 2002 taxation year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit Z.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The CRA's basis for granting the relief on December 5, 2016, was due to possible CRA delay.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit Z.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>34. On May 4, 2017, TaxChambers LLP filed, on behalf of the Applicant, a Second Level Review Request of the CRA's December 5, 2016, decision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit AA.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. On July 19, 2017, the CRA acting on behalf of the Minister, denied the Applicant's Second Level Review Request dated May 4, 2017 for the following relief pursuant to subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>ITA</EM>:
<P1>a. the Cancellation of interest for the 2002 taxation year from January 01, 2006 to May 1, 2008 and March 5, 2013 to October 5, 2016;</P1>
<P1>b. the Cancellation of interest for the 2003 taxation year from January 01, 2006 to May 1, 2008 and June 25, 2011 to October 5, 2016; and</P1>
<P1>c. an agreement to waive any interest that would otherwise accrue on the 2002 and 2003 tax years starting on May 25, 2016.</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>PART II: POINTS IN ISSUE</UNDER></TI>
<P>36. The issue raised in this Application is
<P1>a. was the Minister's decision dated July 19, 2017 to not exercise her discretion pursuant to subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>ITA</EM> unreasonable?</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART III: SUBMISSIONS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK2><N>(a)</N><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>37. According to the Supreme Court of Canada's (the &ldquo;<BOLD>SCC</BOLD>&rdquo;) decision in <CASEREF><SOC>New Brunswick (Board of Management) v. Dunsmuir</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Dunsmuir</EM>&rdquo;), there are two standards of review utilized to review administrative exercises of discretion, correctness and reasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. Furthermore, where a standard of review hsas previously been already determined in the jurisprudence, then that previously determined standard is the appropriate standard of review.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>62</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The applicable standard of review for decisions made by the Minister pursuant to subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>ITA</EM> is that of reasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Telfer v Canada Revenue Agency</SOC><CITE>2009 FCA 23</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>, and <CASEREF><SOC>Easton v Canada (Revenue Agency)</SOC><CITE>2017 FC 113</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. Decisions reviewed on the reasonableness standard will be concerned with &ldquo;the existence of justification, transparency and intelligibility within the decision making process&rdquo; as well as &ldquo;whether the decision falls within a range of possible, acceptable outcomes which are defensible in respect of the facts and the law&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Telfer</EM> at para 25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>(b)</N><TI>Lack of Justification, Transparency, and Intelligibility within Decision Making Process</TI>
<P>40. The Minister's July 19, 2017 decision was based upon the recommendations prepared by Ms. Tracey MacGregor, a CRA delegated official who reviewed the Applicant's Second Level Review Request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, at para 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>41. Ms. MacGregor's understanding of the facts and circumstances during the decision making process of the Applicant's request can be found in Taxpayer Relief Fact Sheet in Section III under the heading &ldquo;Describe the circumstances that prevented the taxpayer from meeting their tax obligations. Were they beyond the taxpayer's control?&rdquo; (&ldquo;<BOLD>Fact Sheet&mdash;Circumstances &amp; Control</BOLD>&rdquo;)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, at p. 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>.</P>
<P>42. Ms. MacGregor has stated in her Affidavit that &ldquo;In making my recommendations with respect to the Second Review Request, I carefully reviewed the following documents and information...&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, at para 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, a review of the Fact Sheet&mdash;Circumstances &amp; Control shows that it is rife with error and misunderstanding as to fundamental facts.</P>
<P>43. As Ms. MacGregor's recommendations were based upon Fact Sheet&mdash;Circumstances &amp; Control, her decision process was premised upon a fundamentally factually erroneous basis.</P>
<P>44. Factual errors and misunderstandings in the Fact Sheet&mdash;Circumstances &amp; Control document include the following which can be found at paragraph 4:
<P1>a. &ldquo;On June 24, 2011, the authorized representative filed a second objection for the 2002 and 2003 tax years; however, on January 4, 2012, it was denied on the reasons that a taxpayer can not [<EM>sic</EM>] object to an arbitrary assessment.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, Exhibit C, at p. 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>.
<P2>i. The Notice of Objection filed on June 24, 2011 was for the 1999 to 2003 and 2009 taxation years, not just for the Applicant's 2002 and 2003 taxation year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit G</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> By narrowly defining the Notice of Objection just the 2002 and 2003 taxation years, Ms. MacGregor has overlooked the fact that at the time the Applicant filed this Notice of Objection, he was dealing with a more complicated fact pattern than just the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.</P2>
<P2>ii. The Notice of Objection for 2002 and 2003 was not denied because &ldquo;a taxpayer can not [<EM>sic</EM>] object to an arbitrary assessment&rdquo;. The Minister initially denied the Notice of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years because &ldquo;In accordance with subsection 165(1.2) of the ITA, no objection may be made by a taxpayer to an assessment in respect of an issue for which the right of objection has been waived in writing under subsection 169(3)&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit H</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This mischaracterization confuses what was a central issue in the delay in processing the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years, which was that the CRA had erroneously cited the application of subsection 165(1.2) of the <EM>ITA</EM> as a bar to accepting the Applicant's Notice of Objection.</P2></P1>
<P1>b. &ldquo;Amended Returns for 2002 and 2003 were then received on March 16, 2012, with no supporting documents or schedules; therefore original returns were requested on March 5, 2013.&rdquo;
<P2>i. The 2002 and 2003 T1 Income Tax Returns that were filed on March 16, 2012, and they contained all of the schedules required to process such returns.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit P.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This misunderstanding characterizes the Applicant in a negative light, when he in fact he had provided the information when required to do so.</P2>
<P2>ii. The 2002 and 2003 T1 Income Tax Returns that were filed were not amended returns, but original returns as the Applicant had not previously filed T1 Income Tax Returns for these two years.</P2>
<P2>iii. &ldquo;original returns&rdquo; were not requested on March 5, 2013.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit N.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead, the March 5, 2013 letter was the first time in which the CRA acknowledged that the Notice of Objection for the 2002 taxation year was valid. Up to that point, Mr. Ranieri had been providing submissions to CRA as to why the Notices of Objection for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years were valid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibits K and M</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Until that preliminary issue was settled, no attention could be devoted to resolving the substantive portion of the Applicant's Notice of Objection.</P2></P1>
<P1>c. &ldquo;In a letter to the taxpayer on April 12, 2013, the appeals officer explained that the 2002 tax year would be reassessed an increase of income due to the court decision for the 1999 to 2001 tax years.&rdquo;
<P2>i. The April 12, 2013 letter from Ms. Farag explains how the reassessments for the 1999 to 2002 taxation years were issued, not how they <EM>will be</EM> issued.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit Q.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This further demonstrates how Ms. MacGregor misunderstood what happened with respect to the Applicant's file during this process.</P2></P1>
<P1>d. &ldquo;On December 6, 2013, the T1 adjustments were denied as the arbitrary assessments were being held up by appeals; therefore; reassessments could not be considered.&rdquo;
<P2>i. On March 5, 2013, Ms. Farag had already indicated to Mr. Ranieri that the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2003 taxation year was invalid. As such, it is unclear how the Minister could, on the one hand, deny processing the Applicant's return for the 2003 taxation year because it was being &ldquo;held up by appeals&rdquo; and on the other hand, have the CRA Appeals Division state that the 2003 Notice of Objection was invalid. This letter only perpetuated the confusion that the Applicant and his representatives had with respect to the validity of the 2003 Notice of Objection.</P2>
<P2>ii. Secondly, if the returns that were filed for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years were being &ldquo;held up by appeals&rdquo;, the CRA Appeals Division must have had an opportunity to have review the 2002 and 2003 T1 income tax returns that had been filed by the Applicant on March 16, 2012. However, there is nothing in the materials provided by the Respondent pursuant to the Applicant's request made pursuant to Rule 317 of the <EM>Federal Courts Rules</EM> or the Affidavit of Ms. MacGregor that would indicate at what point in time after March 16, 2012 the CRA Appeals Division would have began to look at the 2002 and 2003 T1 Income Tax Returns. It does not appear as if Ms. MacGregor apprised herself of the facts as to what was actually happening within the CRA during this period of time, despite there being multiple requests and officers all working on the Applicant's matter.</P2></P1>
<P1>e. &ldquo;The Appeals Officer issued the taxpayer a letter on May 5, 2014, requesting the 2002 original return be submit by June 5, 2014&rdquo;.
<P2>i. The May 5, 2014 letter is a request for &ldquo;related schedules and any supporting documentation&rdquo; with respect to the 2002 taxation year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit S</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P2>
<P2>ii. The May 5, 2014 letter confirms that the Applicant had already provided the Agency with an amended T1 Return for 2002.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit S</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P2>
<P2>iii. The May 5, 2014 letter itself contains its own error in that it states that the applicant has not provided the related schedules.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit S.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, the Applicant had already provided the T1 Income Tax Returns, with the related schedules, on two occasions&mdash;March 16, 2012 and April 10, 2013.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit O and Exhibit P.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P2>
<P2>iv. There is no indication in the record why no CRA Appeals Officer communicated with Mr. Ranieri until over a year after his April 10, 2013 fax other than to explain how the disputed 2002 Notice of Reassessment originated. These unexplained CRA delays were the heart of the Applicant's request for taxpayer relief that were overlooked by Ms. MacGregor due to her misunderstanding of the facts.</P2></P1>
<P1>f. &ldquo;The 2002 return was received on June 4, 2014, and the 2002 objection was allowed and $154,000 in income was cancelled on September 5, 2014.&rdquo;
<P2>i. On June 4<SUP>th</SUP>, 2014, Mr. Ranieri submitted two faxes to Ms. Aman. The first fax contained financial statements, not a tax return, as supporting documentation<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit T.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. The second fax contained submissions explaining why the financial statements support the Applicant's position.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit U.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P2></P1></P>
<P>45. Furthermore, Ms. MacGregor's lack of clear understanding of the facts is readily apparent even in her Affidavit, where in paragraph 12 she states that &ldquo;In coming to my recommendation for granting the applicant partial interest relief, I also confirmed and considered the fact that the applicant has been granted relief of the arrears interest assessed on his 2002 and 2003 taxation years from June 24, 2011 to March 5, 2013, due to CRA delay pursuant to his first request for Taxpayer Relief.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, para. 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This statement is incorrect because according to the CRA's original December 5, 2016 decision letter, such interest relief was limited to 2002 only and was not allowed with respect to the 2003 taxation year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, Exhibit B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>(c)</N><TI>Outcome Indefensible In Respect of the Facts</TI>
<P>46. The Applicant submits that July 19, 2017 decision was an outcome indefensible in respect of the facts.</P>
<P>47. IC07-1 <EM>Taxpayer Relief Provisions</EM> (&ldquo;<BOLD>IC07-1</BOLD>&rdquo;) set out the conditions where the Minister will exercise discretion under subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>ITA</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IC07-1, <EM>Taxpayer Relief Provisions</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>g. IC07-1 (of which subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>ITA</EM> is included) allows the CRA to help taxpayers to resolve issues that come up through no fault of their own.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IC07-1, at para 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>h. Paragraph 26 of IC07-1 states that penalties and interest may also be waived or cancelled if they resulted mainly because of actions of the CRA, such as (c) incorrect information provided to a taxpayer or (f) undue delays in resolving an objection or an appeal, or in completing an audit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IC07-1, at para 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>48. As noted above, the Applicant was granted interest relief for the 2002 taxation year for the period June 24, 2011 to December March 5, 2013.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, Exhibit B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The basis for this relief was due to the fact that the Applicant's representative, Mr. Ranieri, received communication from the CRA indicating that the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2002 taxation year was invalid, when it was not actually invalid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, Exhibit B, pages 1 and 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>49. However, the Minister did not find that there was any CRA delay in processing the Applicant's objection for the 2002 taxation year after March 5, 2013 or with respect to the 2003 taxation year after June 24, 2011 at either the first Taxpayer Relief Request or the Second Level Review Request. The Applicant submits that this decision is unreasonable because it is not defensible in respect of the facts, as the following delays did occur:
<QUOTE><P>i. Delay #1: between March 6, 2013 to May 5, 2014 for the 2002 taxation year:
<P1>i. The processing of the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2002 taxation year was marred by delay and confusion upon its filing in June, 2011.</P1>
<P1>ii. The Minister admitted its delay and miscommunication in processing the Applicant's Objection for the 2002 taxation year, but by limiting the relief it granted to March 5, 2013, the Minister is taking the position that this delay and confusion ended on that date. The Applicant respectfully disagrees with that position.</P1>
<P1>iii. As stated above, Mr. Ranieri faxed a copy of the Applicant's 2002 T1 Income Tax Return to the Appeals Officer who wrote the March 5, 2013 letter to the Applicant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit O.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>iv. Two days later, Ms. Farag wrote back to Mr. Ranieri to confirm how the 1999 to 2002 taxation years were reassessed. This letter does not mention the Applicant's fax sent two days earlier.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit Q.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>v. The Applicant did not receive any correspondence from an Appeals Officer until over one year later when Ms. Aman writes to the Applicant requesting further supporting documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit S.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>vi. There is no explanation provided as to why neither Ms. Farag nor Ms. Aman failed to correspond with the Applicant or his representative during this period.</P1>
<P1>vii. Ms. Farag and Ms. Aman had ample time to review the fax dated April 10, 2013 and to generate a list of further questions.</P1>
<P1>viii. Given that Ms. Aman incorrectly stated that the Applicant had submitted his return without schedules, it leaves the Applicant wondering how much attention was actually given to the April 10, 2013 fax.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit O.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>ix. The Applicant submits that it is not justifiable for the Minister to have accepted that she delayed the processing of the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2002 taxation year from June 24, 2011 to March 5, 2013 but that there were no further delays until May 5, 2014.</P1>
<P1>x. The Applicant submits that Ms. MacGregor's misunderstanding of the facts lead to her unreasonable conclusion that the delay in processing the Applicant's objection for the 2002 taxation year after March 5, 2013 was due to the inaction of either the Applicant or his representative.</P1>
<P1>xi. Upon a review of the record, the conclusion defensible in respect of the facts is that between March 6, 2013 and May 5, 2014, the CRA took no further action to resolve the Applicant's 2002 objection. Accordingly, the Applicant submits that this is grounds for the cancellation of interest that accrued between March 6, 2013 and May 5, 2014 pursuant to paragraph 26(f) of IC07-1.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IC07-1, at para 26(f).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>j. Delay #2: between June 24, 2011 to December 6, 2013 for the 2003 taxation year:
<P1>i. The Minister found that there were no delays with respect to the 2003 taxation year after June 24, 2011. The Applicant respectfully disagrees.</P1>
<P1>ii. On June 24, 2011, Mr. Ranieri filed a Notice of Objection which included the 2003 taxation year. At the time of the Objection, the Applicant was under the impression that the date of Reassessment was April 8, 2010 and that the Objection was valid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit G.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>iii. Until January 4, 2012, the Applicant had no reason to believe that his Notice of Objection was not filed on a timely basis.</P1>
<P1>iv. On January 4, 2012, the Minister issued a letter stating that both the 2002 and 2003 taxation years could not be accepted pursuant to subsection 169(3) of the <EM>ITA</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit H.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>v. In addition to the Applicant's Notice of Objection for the 2003 taxation year, on March 16, 2012, the Applicant filed T1 income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Affidavit, tab I, page 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>vi. As such, between March 16, 2012 and March 5, 2013, the Applicant believed that there were two processes that were being worked with the Minister to resolve the 2003 taxation year.</P1>
<P1>vii. While Mr. Ranieri's submissions with respect to the validity of the notice of objection for the 2003 taxation year continued until March 5, 2013, there is no indication that the Applicant's T1 Income Tax Returns that were filed on March 16, 2012 were being processed.</P1>
<P1>viii. According to Mr. Ranieri, the CRA failed to communicate with him until September, 2014, when he was contacted by phone by Mr. Pagonis.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit R.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>ix. Shortly thereafter, on October 2, 2013, Mr. Pagonis informed Mr. Ranieri that because Objections had been filed, he could not consider them under this process.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit R.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>x. This timeline was confirmed by Ms. MacGregor as part of her report to the ultimate decision-makers, Ms. Lori Beck and Mr. Dean Rush.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Tracy MacGregor, Exhibit C, bottom paragraph, page 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>xi. However, by March 5, 2013, Ms. Farag had already confirmed that the Notice of Objection for the 2003 taxation year was not valid.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Robert Jewett, Exhibit N.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>xii. As such, it is unclear why the processing of the T1 Income Tax Return for the 2003 taxation year would otherwise be delayed when the CRA Appeals Division was not considering that a valid objection had been filed for that year.</P1>
<P1>xiii. The Minister's decision is not defensible in respect of the facts because between June 24, 2011 and December 5, 2013, the Applicant was undertaking all options available to him to resolve his tax debt for the 2003 taxation year.</P1>
<P1>xiv. This resolution process was unnecessarily delayed until March 5, 2013, because of the confusion as to the validity of the 2003 objection that was created by CRA's correspondence of January 4, 2012, and thereafter until December 6, 2013, because CRA was not processing the T1 income tax returns because of a mistaken belief that that year was being dealt with by the CRA Appeals Division. The Applicant submits that this is grounds for relief pursuant to IC07-1 paragraph 26(f), as the process pursued by the Applicant is similar to an objection or an appeal.</P1></P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V"><UNDER>PART IV: ORDER SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>50. The Applicant respectfully requests that this application for judicial review be allowed with costs to the Applicant, and the decision of July 19, 2017 be set aside, and the matter remitted to another decision-maker for re-determination.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
