<BLOCK1><TI>RESPONDENT'S MEMORANDUM OF FACT AND LAW</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">OVERVIEW</TI>
<P><P1>1. The Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;), in exercising the discretion conferred upon her under subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5th Supp.), as amended (the &ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;), allowed in part the Applicant's request for waiver of interest in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years, the decision of which was communicated to the Applicant by letter dated July 19, 2017 (the &ldquo;Decision&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>2. The Decision granted the Applicant interest relief in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years from May 2, 2008 up to June 24, 2011 due to actions of the Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;). The Applicant seeks judicial review of the Decision.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART I&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P><P1>3. The facts relevant to the review of the Decision are set out in the affidavit of Robert Jewett, sworn September 6, 2017 (the &ldquo;Applicant's Affidavit&rdquo;) and the affidavit of Tracey MacGregor, sworn October 11, 2017 (the &ldquo;Respondent's Affidavit&rdquo;).</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI>History of Assessments and Objections re: Applicant's 2002 and 2003 Tax Years</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>ITA ss. 152(7) Assessments, Objections and Confirmation</EM></TI>
<P><P1>4. The Applicant did not file income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 tax years as and when required by the <EM>Act</EM>.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 02 and Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;: Reproduction of Letter from CRA to Robert Jewett dated September 04, 2007.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>5. The Minister assessed the Applicant's tax liability under the <EM>Act</EM> for the 2002 and 2003 tax years, the concurrent notices of which were dated February 1, 2008 (collectively the &ldquo;Assessments&rdquo;). The Assessments were made under subsection 152(7) of the <EM>Act</EM>.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 02 and Exhibits &ldquo;D&rdquo;, &ldquo;E&rdquo; and &ldquo;F&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>6. The Applicant objected to the Assessments, the notices of which were received by the Minister on May 2, 2008.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03 and Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>7. The Minister confirmed the Assessments, the notice of which was dated June 25, 2009.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03 and Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>8. The Applicant did not appeal the Assessments to the Tax Court of Canada.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Tax Court Judgment and Consequential Assessment of 2002 Tax Year</EM></TI>
<P><P1>9. On November 29, 2009, the Tax Court of Canada rendered judgment in respect of an appeal from the Minister's assessments of the Applicant's tax liability under the <EM>Act</EM> for the 1999, 2000 and 2001 tax years (the &ldquo;Judgment&rdquo;).
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>10. The Judgment, among other things, referred the Applicant's 2001 tax year back to the Minister for reconsideration and reassessment on the basis that &ldquo;...the $47,576 credit card balance from 2001, should be removed from personal expenditures in 2001 and put in 2002.&rdquo;
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo; at para. 30 (p. 39 of 755).</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>11. The Minister reassessed the Applicant's tax liability under the <EM>Act</EM> for the 2002 tax year, the notice of which was dated April 8, 2010, to implement the Judgment (the &ldquo;Consequential Assessment&rdquo;).
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibits</BOLD> &ldquo;F&rdquo; <BOLD>and &ldquo;Q&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Applicant's Objection re: 2002 Tax Year</EM></TI>
<P><P1>12. The Applicant objected to the Consequential Assessment i.e. the reassessment of the 2002 tax year, the notice of which was received by the Minister on June 24, 2011. The notice also purported to object to the Minister's assessment of the Applicant's 2003 tax year.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>13. In the period from June 24, 2011 to March 5, 2013, communication from the CRA to the Applicant erroneously stated that the Minister cannot accept an objection to the Consequential Assessment when in fact such an objection may be valid.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibits &ldquo;H&rdquo;, &ldquo;J&rdquo; and &ldquo;K&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>14. On or about March 5, 2013, the CRA communicated with the Applicant and provide him with the correct information with respect to his objection for the 2002 tax year, including the fact that the objection is valid and active.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>15. The Minister allowed the Applicant's objection for the 2002 tax year in part, the decision of which was communicated to the Applicant by letter dated July 24, 2014.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;W&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;, Page 03.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<BLOCK5><TI><EM>First Level Review</EM></TI>
<P><P1>16. In May 2016, the Applicant applied to the Minister for waiver of interest for the 2002 and 2003 tax years (the &ldquo;First Level Request&rdquo;).
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;Y&rdquo;</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at para. 4.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>17. The Minister made the decision to allow the Applicant's request in part, and granted the applicant interest relief in respect of the 2002 tax year from June 24, 2011 up to March 5, 2013, the decision of which was communicated to the Applicant by letter dated December 5, 2016 (the &ldquo;First Level Decision&rdquo;).
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at para. 6 and Exhibits &ldquo;A&rdquo; and &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Second Level Request and Decision</EM></TI>
<P><P1>18. In May 2017, the Applicant applied to the Minister for reconsideration of the First Level Decision (the &ldquo;Second Level Request&rdquo;).
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit, Exhibit &ldquo;AA&rdquo;</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at para. 7.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>19. In reviewing the Second Level Request, the Minister determined that the Second Level Request should be allowed in part, and that interest relief be granted for the 2002 and 2003 tax years from May 2, 2008 to June 24, 2011 due to CRA delay.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at para. 8 to 10 and Exhibits &ldquo;C&rdquo; to &ldquo;I&rdquo;, inclusive.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART II&mdash;POINTS IN ISSUE</TI>
<P><P1>20. The sole issue in this application is whether the Decision is reasonable.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART III&mdash;SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>A</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Standard of Review</EM></TI>
<P><P1>21. Subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Act</EM> confers upon the Minister the discretion to waive interest imposed under the <EM>Act</EM>. The exercise of the Minister's discretion under this subsection is an administrative decision subject to review by the Court.</P1>
<P1>22. In reviewing an administrative decision, the reviewing court must determine the proper standard of review. There are only two standards of review applicable to judicial reviews of administrative decisions: correctness and reasonableness.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Dunsmuir v. New Brunswick</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 9</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Dunsmuir</EM>], at para. 34</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>23. In <EM>Telfer</EM>, the Federal Court of Appeal held that the standard of review applicable to decisions made under subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Act</EM> is (un)reasonableness.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Telfer v. Canada (Revenue Agency)</SOC><CITE>2009 FCA 23</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2></P1>
<P1>24. In <EM>Dunsmuir</EM>, the Supreme Court elaborated on the reasonableness standard in the context of judicial review:
<QUOTE><P>Reasonableness is a deferential standard animated by the principle that underlies the development of the two previous standards of reasonableness: certain questions that come before administrative tribunals do not lend themselves to one specific, particular result. Instead they may give rise to a number of possible, reasonable conclusions. Tribunals have a margin of appreciation within the range of acceptable and rational solutions. <UNDER>A court conducting a review for reasonableness inquires into the qualities that make a decision reasonable, referring both to the process of articulating the reasons and to outcomes. In judicial review, reasonableness is concerned mostly with the existence of justification, transparency and intelligibility within the decision-making process. But it is also concerned with whether the decision falls within a range of possible, acceptable outcomes which are defensible in respect of the facts and law.</UNDER>
<P1>(my emphasis)</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P2><BOLD><EM>Dunsmuir</EM>, at para. 47</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>25. A decision-maker is not required to make an explicit finding on each constituent element, however subordinate, leading to its final conclusion. If the reasons given allow the reviewing court to understand why a decision was made and permit it to determine whether the conclusion is within the range of acceptable outcomes, the <EM>Dunsmuir</EM> criteria are met.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>N.L.N.U. v. Newfoundland &amp; Labrador (Treasury Board)</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 62</CITE><PARANUM>15 and 16</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>B</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Taxpayer Relief Policy</EM></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Income Tax Information Circular IC07-1</EM></TI>
<P><P1>26. The CRA guideline sets out a non-exhaustive list of factors that will be considered by the Minister in exercising her discretion to waive interest, including:
<P2>a. extraordinary circumstances;</P2>
<P2>b. actions of the CRA; and</P2>
<P2>c. inability to pay or financial hardship.</P2>
<P2><BOLD>Income Tax Information Circular IC07-1 (&ldquo;IC07-1&rdquo;) at para. 23</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>27. Actions of the CRA that may have prevented a taxpayer from making a payment when due, filing a return on time, or otherwise complying with an obligation under the <EM>Act</EM> include, but are not limited to, the following:
<P2>a. processing delays that result in the taxpayer not being informed, within a reasonable time, that an amount was owing;</P2>
<P2>b. errors in material available to the public, which led taxpayers to file returns or make payments based on incorrect information;</P2>
<P2>c. incorrect information provided to a taxpayer;</P2>
<P2>d. error in processing;</P2>
<P2>e. delays in providing information, such as when a taxpayer could not make the appropriate instalment or arrears payments because the necessary information was not available; or</P2>
<P2>f. undue delays in resolving an objection or an appeal, or in completing an audit.</P2>
<P2><BOLD>IC07-1, at para. 26</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>28. When determining whether to exercise her discretion to waive interest, the following factors will be considered by the Minister:
<P2>a. whether the taxpayer has a history of compliance with tax obligations;</P2>
<P2>b. whether the taxpayer has knowingly allowed a balance to exist on which arrears interest has accrued;</P2>
<P2>c. whether the taxpayer has exercised a reasonable amount of care and has not been negligent or careless in conducting their affairs under the self-assessment system; and</P2>
<P2>d. whether the taxpayer has acted quickly to remedy any delay or omission.</P2>
<P2><BOLD>IC07-1, at para. 33</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>29. While taxpayers are generally considered responsible for errors made or delays caused by third parties acting for the taxpayer for income tax matters, there may be exceptional situations where it may be appropriate to provide relief to taxpayers because of third- party errors or delays.
<P2><BOLD>IC07-1, at para. 35</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>C</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Decision was Reasonable</EM></TI>
<P><P1>30. The subject of this judicial review is the Decision and whether it was reasonable. As explained by the Supreme Court in <EM>Dunsmuir</EM>, a review for reasonableness is an inquiry into both the process of articulating the reasons and to outcomes. The review of the Decision is therefore a determination of the following:
<P2>a. whether the decision-making process of the Minister in coming to the Decision was justified, transparent and intelligible; and</P2>
<P2>b. whether the Decision falls within a range of possible, acceptable outcomes which are defensible in respect of the facts and law.</P2></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Decision / Interest Relief re: 2002 and 2003 Tax Years</EM></TI>
<P><P1>31. The Decision granted the Applicant interest relief in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years from May 2, 2008 up to June 24, 2011 due to CRA delays.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>32. The relief granted by the Decision is in addition to the interest relief in respect of the 2002 tax year from June 24, 2011 up to March 5, 2013 already granted by the Minister in the First Level Decision.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at para. 6 and Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>33. The cumulative interest relief granted by the Minister to the Applicant in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years is therefore as follows:
<P2>a. for the 2002 tax year&mdash;from May 2, 2008 up to March 5, 2013; and</P2>
<P2>b. for the 2003 tax year&mdash;from May 2, 2008 up to June 24, 2011.</P2></P1>
<P1>34. The Minister reviewed the CRA records and the Applicant's submissions, and determined that the Applicant did not warrant any further interest relief in respect of the 2002 and 2003 tax years.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; Page 05</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Applicant's History of Compliance / Conduct of Affairs under Self-Assessment System</EM></TI>
<P><P1>35. The Applicant did not file his income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 tax years as and when required by the <EM>Act</EM>.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; Page 02</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>36. The Minister issued a warning letter to the Applicant with respect to his failure to file income tax returns for the 2002 and 2003 tax years, and subsequent to the Assessments, issued multiple warning letters to the Applicant with respect to his significant income tax arrears for multiple tax years including the 2002 and 2003 tax years.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; Page 02-03 and Exhibits &ldquo;D&rdquo;, &ldquo;E&rdquo;, &ldquo;H&rdquo; and &ldquo;I&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Errors Made by Applicant's Lawyer Compounded by CRA Delays</EM></TI>
<P><P1>37. The Applicant did not appeal the Assessments to the Tax Court of Canada, which was attributed to errors made by his lawyers.
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; Pages 03-04</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>38. The CRA communication with the Applicant between June 25, 2009 and June 24, 2011 compounded the problem of the errors made by the Applicant's lawyer by not providing the following information clearly to the Applicant:
<P2>a. the Consequential Assessment was issued to implement the Judgment and was with respect to the 2002 tax year only, which the Applicant may object to and the Minister will process the objection to the Consequential Assessment; and</P2>
<P2>b. the Minister did not reassess the Applicant's 2003 tax year, and since the Minister confirmed the Assessments on June 25, 2009, the Applicant needed to appeal to the Tax Court to dispute the assessment with respect to the 2003 tax year.</P2>
<P2><BOLD>Respondent's Affidavit at Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; Pages 03-05</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>39. The Minister considered the incorrect information provided to the Applicant with respect to the objections with respect to the 2002 and 2003 tax years and concluded that these were actions of the CRA that caused delay. On that basis, the Minister determined that interest relief should be granted for the 2002 and 2003 tax years from May 2, 2008 up to June 24, 2011, which covers the period from when the Applicant first objected to the Assessments to when the Applicant first objected to the Consequential Assessment.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>No CRA Delay re: 2002 Tax Year from March 6, 2013 to May 5, 2014</EM></TI>
<P><P1>40. The period from March 6, 2013 to May 5, 2014 was when the Minister processed the Applicant's objection to the Consequential Assessment i.e. the 2002 tax year. The Applicant and the CRA were engaged in ongoing correspondence with respect to the objection during this period in the usual course of resolving an objection.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit at Exhibits &ldquo;O&rdquo;, &ldquo;P&rdquo;, &ldquo;Q&rdquo;, &ldquo;R&rdquo;, &ldquo;S&rdquo; and &ldquo;T&rdquo;.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>41. The Respondent submits that it was not unreasonable for CRA to take 14 months to resolve the Applicant's objection with respect to the Consequential Assessment.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Metro-Can Construction Limited v. R.</SOC><CITE>2002 FCT 1171</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P2></P1>
<P1>42. Furthermore, the Applicant had a right to appeal the Consequential Assessment to the Tax Court at any time during the period from March 6, 2013 to May 5, 2014.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>No CRA Delay re: 2003 Tax Year from June 24, 2011 to December 6, 2013</EM></TI>
<P><P1>43. The Applicant did not have a valid objection with the Minister with respect to the 2003 tax year in the period from June 24, 2011 to December 6, 2013 and therefore there were no CRA delays.</P1>
<P1>44. A review of the correspondence between the Applicant and CRA during this period shows that while the Applicant's lawyer consistently and incorrectly referenced the 2003 tax year as a year under objection, the CRA has never stated that the Applicant has a valid objection with respect to the 2003 tax year.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit at Exhibits &ldquo;G&rdquo;, &ldquo;H&rdquo;, &ldquo;I&rdquo;, &ldquo;K&rdquo;, &ldquo;L&rdquo;</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>45. In particular, the CRA letter to the Applicant dated December 19, 2012 clearly referenced the Minister's confirmation with respect to the 2003 tax year, and by February 1, 2013, the Applicant's lawyer stopped referencing the 2003 tax year in his letters to CRA.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit at Exhibits &ldquo;J&rdquo; and &ldquo;M&rdquo;</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>46. Finally, the CRA letter to the Applicant dated March 5, 2013 stated clearly that the Applicant did not have an objection with the Minister with respect to the 2003 tax year.
<P2><BOLD>Applicant's Affidavit at Exhibit</BOLD> &ldquo;N&rdquo;</P2></P1>
<P1>47. The Respondent submits that if there were any delays with respect to the 2003 tax year in the period June 24, 2011 to December 6, 2013, the delays were due to errors made by the Applicant's lawyer, and that such errors were not compounded by any actions of the CRA.</P1>
<P1>48. Subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Act</EM> grants broad discretion to the Minister to allow relief or partial relief. In the present case, the Minister's discretion was properly exercised. The Minister took into account the relevant factors in her consideration of the Applicant's circumstances in coming to the Decision. The Decision to waive interest for the 2002 and 2003 tax years from May 2, 2008 up to June 24, 2011 was reasonable.</P1>
<P1>49. The Decision granted the Applicant interest relief and the Respondent submits that the outcome is within the range of acceptable and rational solutions contemplated by <EM>Dunsmuir</EM>. While the Applicant may argue that the Minister could have more generous, such is not the test for whether or not the Decision was reasonable.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>APL Properties Ltd. v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2013 FC 449</CITE><PARANUM>39 and 46</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>D</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Paragraph 45 of Applicant's Memorandum re: Paragraph 12 of the Respondent's Affidavit</EM></TI>
<P><P1>50. The Respondent concedes that paragraph 12 of the Respondent's Affidavit contained an error. The First Level Decision granted interest relief for the Applicant's 2002 tax year only, and therefore the reference to relief for &ldquo;...2002 <BOLD><UNDER>and 2003</UNDER></BOLD> taxation years...&rdquo; in paragraph 12 of the Respondent's Affidavit is incorrect.</P1>
<P1>51. However, the Respondent submits that the error in paragraph 12 of the Respondent's Affidavit has no bearing on the Decision under review for the following reasons:
<P2>a. the error is patently obvious as it is contradicted by the exhibits annexed to the Respondent's Affidavit, in particular, <BOLD>Exhibits &ldquo;A&rdquo;, &ldquo;B&rdquo; and &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD>; and</P2>
<P2>b. the Respondent's Affidavit was prepared in the course of this proceeding and was not a document prepared in the course of or considered by the Minister in the process of making the Decision.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>E</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Conclusion</EM></TI>
<P><P1>52. The Minister's decision-making process was justifiable, transparent and intelligible. The Minister exercised her statutory discretion in good faith and observed the principles of natural justice, and made a reasonable decision based on the relevant facts and considerations before her. The Applicant was permitted the opportunity to make representations and those representations were fully reviewed and considered by the Minister. The reasons for Decision were then clearly communicated to the Applicant. The Decision falls within a range of possible, acceptable outcomes.</P1>
<P1>53. The Decision was reasonable, and deference should be accorded to the same.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>54. The Respondent requests that this application be dismissed with costs.</P1></P>
